n=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: In keeping with the self pity day today</span><hr size=1> I have been in your shoes as well, Kestri. My grandfather died about 5 years ago, when he was living with us. He smoked alot, and he was hospitalized with Emphazeema (however you spell it). <br>
<br>
I never cried when he died, I don't know why I didn't cry. It was the oddest feeling, coming home after school and not seeing him home, knowing I'd never see him again. EVER.<br>
<br>
Then about a year later it just.. hit me. That he was really, actually gone. It was the first time for me that someone had ever left my life and no matter how hard I tried, I could never get them back or see or talk to them ever again. It was permement, and he was gone. I cried when I realized this.<br>
<br>
People mourn/suffer inthier own ways. When I'm hurt or sad, I usually just start talking, saying what's on my mind or how I feel. It gets me in loads of trouble, but at least it feels better after getting it out of me. I'm a fairly quiet person otherwise. Many people take advantage of me when I'm talking about my feelings, and on the internet people have barely any emotion at all. Cruelty is very common here. I'm not going to suggest anything, just speaking from experience.<br>
<br>
I do know what you went through/are still going through, and I offer any sympathy you need. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#414141><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uchants.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Chants</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Guardian of Underfoot</span><br>  Posts: 843<br> <font color=#CC9900>(6/22/01 9:25:21 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: In keeping with the self pity day today</span><hr size=1> I am sorry Kestri.<br>
<br>
Allow me to share with you a similar experience of my own.  About 6 years ago, I was an attorney with a solo practice.  One morning, I got a call from a hospital in Morehead City, North Carolina.  I spoke with a nurse, and then a doctor.<br>
<br>
I tried to make some small talk with the nurse, letting her know that I loved Morehead as I went to camp there when I was young.  She made some comment, I don't remember, then said that I better speak with the doctor.<br>
<br>
I had no idea what this call was about.  Then the doctor started talking about my mother, how a rescue team had pulled her out of the Atlantic, how they performed mouth to mouth, and eventually, that she had drowned.  <br>
<br>
She had been camping with a friend of hers.  The camp site was next to the beach.  While swimming, she was pulled out in a rip tide and could not get back in.  The only next of kin they could find was me, since she had my business card on her.  So I got the call.<br>
<br>
Kestri, these things will happen several more times in what I hope is a long life for you.  And time will heal the pain that you're feeling right now.  But never completely.  The emotional wound will heal, become a scar, and the scar will get smaller and smaller, until it is just a pin point.  The pin point is there to remind you of your Great Uncle.  For whatever reason, our humanity will not let us forget these events, no matter how painful. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#313532><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ugarrdor.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Garrdor</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Traveller of Underfoot</span><br>  Posts: 201<br> <font color=#CC9900>(6/22/01 9:45:23 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www2.arnes.si/~kpjdd5/runroom.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: In keeping with the self pity day today</span><hr size=1> Poor Kestri, I know how you feel. Very sad. It's hard losing someone that close to you.<br>
<br>
Myself, watched and heard a close family member trapped in a car, burning alive. I still can't sleep.<br>
<br>
Kestri, you should be thankful that you did not have to see your uncle while he had cancer. My dad had cancer of the brain. He lost most of his memory when he went through Kemo-Therapy and lost his salivia glands as well. He is still alive, but he is a different person/has seizures often. <p>-Garrdor Earthdancer
